❯ Yes I agree, but is there a way that we can 'remember' the user's scroll position on each page so that when they revisit that page, it scrolls them to where they last left off?

● Yes, absolutely doable — and a lovely touch. Before navigating away from a month, save its scroll position to
  sessionStorage keyed by month (e.g. scroll_2026-03 = 1840). When returning to that month, restore it.

  One thing worth noting: sessionStorage lives for the tab's lifetime only — it clears when the tab closes. If you
  want scroll position to survive across separate visits (open the site tomorrow and resume where you left off),
  localStorage would do that instead. The tradeoff is localStorage persists indefinitely, which could mean
  restoring a stale position if new articles have been added above where the user was.

  My recommendation: sessionStorage — remembers within a visit (including navigating away and back), but resets on
  a fresh session. Clean and no stale-position weirdness.

  Does that sound right, or would you prefer the longer-lived localStorage version?

